SYND WSJ-PRO-NP CODES_REVIEWED Asia News </DescField><DescField fid="ipcns">OASN </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">World</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Captain of Shipwrecked North Korean Fishing Boat Gets Suspended Sentence in Japan; North Korean fishing boat captain Kang Myong Hak will likely be deported</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>TOKYO—A North Korean fishing boat captain who admitted stealing goods from a Japanese island after getting shipwrecked was given a suspended sentence Tuesday by a Japanese court and is expected to return home.</Para><Para>A district court judge in the northern city of Hakodate sentenced Kang Myong Hak, 45, to two years and six months in prison but suspended the sentence for four years, a court official said, meaning he doesn't have to serve the time if he abides by the law during the four-year period. A representative of the regional immigration office said Mr. Kang was likely to be deported to North Korea.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>In a hearing on March 9, Mr. Kang, captain of a squid-fishing boat with 10 men aboard, <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trial-of-a-shipwrecked-north-korean-calls-attention-to-sanctions-1520587156">admitted to stealing items</ELink> including a generator, solar panels and a television from a shelter on an uninhabited island off the coast of Hokkaido in northern Japan. He said the ship's engine and rudder were broken and after two months at sea, the men would have died if they hadn't found the island.</Para><Para>He said he told the crew to take items from the shelter, used by the local fishery association, to raise their spirits.</Para><Para>Mr. Kang's boat was one of a record 104 <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korean-fishermen-adrift-for-months-wash-up-in-japan-1512483105">North Korean fishing vessels to wash up in Japan</ELink> last year, according to the Japanese Coast Guard. Japanese officials have speculated that the rising number may be related to pressure on North Korea's economy from international sanctions.</Para><Para>Eight of the 10 men on Mr. Kang's boat have already been repatriated to North Korea, while one is being treated in a Japanese hospital for tuberculosis. Mr. Kang was the only man charged.</Para><Para>Write to Chieko Tsuneoka at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:chieko.Tsuneoka@dowjones.com">chieko.Tsuneoka@dowjones.com</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Chieko Tsuneoka </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/captain-of-shipwrecked-north-korean-fishing-boat-gets-suspended-sentence-in-japan-1522129973" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

